rovider\n```\n\n`View()` is called on **every** `spinner.TickMsg` (fires continuously while any provider is running) and rescans every line of every provider's full history with a string-prefix check, every single frame. This is the closest analog to an N+1: O(providers × total accumulated lines) work repeated many times per second for a value that only actually changes when a new `\"  - \"` line arrives.\n\n**Fix — maintain a running counter, updated once per incoming line:**\n```go\ntype providerStatus struct {\n\tstate   providerState\n\tlines   []string\n\tsaved   int // incremented once per matching line\n}\n\n// in the statusMsg case of Update():\nst.lines = append(st.lines, msg.line)\nif strings.HasPrefix(msg.line, \"  - \") {\n\tst.saved++\n}\n```\nThen `viewRunning` reads `st.saved` directly — O(1) per provider instead of O(lines).\n\n## 3. Process-spawn overhead (N+1 analog) — `runCrawler`/`startRun` (main.go:59-78, tui.go:254-274)\n\nEach selected provider spawns its **own** `uv run main.py <name>` subprocess (main.go:60). That's `uv`'s dependency-resolution + Python interpreter startup cost paid once per provider (up to 11x for \"all\"), rather than one warm process handling every provider in a loop. If `apps/crawler/main.py` can accept multiple provider names in one invocation, batching into a single subprocess (or a small pool) would cut that fixed per-process overhead by ~10x for full runs. I couldn't verify this from `apps/cli` alone — worth checking `apps/crawler/main.py`'s arg parsing.\n\n## 4. Unbounded memory growth\n\n`providerStatus.lines` (tui.go:36) accumulates every stdout line for the life of the run with no cap — for `--limit 0` (\"run until exhausted\") this is unbounded. Combined with issue #1, memory and CPU both scale with total output. Consider capping displayed history (e.g. keep last N lines for the viewport) while keeping the `saved` counter (fix #2) independent of the retained line count.\n\n## 5. No subprocess cancellation/timeout (resource-leak risk)\n\n`exec.Command` in `runCrawler` (main.go:60) is created with no `context.Context` and no timeout. If a provider hangs, `cmd.Wait()` blocks its goroutine forever — and the UI has no way to kill it (`q`/`ctrl+c` are no-ops while `m.pending != 0`, handleKey tui.go:147-150). If the parent process is ever force-killed externally, these children can be orphaned.\n\n**Fix:** use `exec.CommandContext` with a per-provider timeout, and wire `ctrl+c` while running to cancel contexts and forcibly quit rather than blocking.\n\n---\n\n**Not applicable to this codebase:** no database (no N+1 queries in the SQL sense), no React (Bubble Tea's `View()` is full-redraw-by-design, so \"unnecessary re-renders\" isn't the right frame — the fix is making what's redrawn cheap, which is #1/#2 above).\n\nWant me to apply fixes #1 and #2 (the two concrete, low-risk ones)?\n",
